abstract: Already comfortable as an outlier in her party, Democratic presidential candidate Tulsi Gabbard did not support the impeachment of President Donald Trump, voting “present” Wednesday on two articles that cleared the House.
snippet: Already comfortable as an outlier in her party, Democratic presidential candidate Tulsi Gabbard did not support the impeachment of President Donald Trump, voting “present” Wednesday on two articles that cleared the House.
lead_paragraph: Already comfortable as an outlier in her party, Democratic presidential candidate Tulsi Gabbard did not support the impeachment of President Donald Trump, voting “present” Wednesday on two articles that cleared the House.
headline_main: Defying Party, Gabbard Votes 'Present' on Trump Impeachment
headline_print_headline: Defying Party, Gabbard Votes 'Present' on Trump Impeachment

abstract: Three lawmakers — Republican Reps. John Shimkus of Illinois and Duncan Hunter of California and Democratic Rep. Jose Serrano of New York — missed the historic House votes to impeach President Donald Trump.
snippet: Three lawmakers — Republican Reps. John Shimkus of Illinois and Duncan Hunter of California and Democratic Rep. Jose Serrano of New York — missed the historic House votes to impeach President Donald Trump.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Three lawmakers — Republican Reps. John Shimkus of Illinois and Duncan Hunter of California and Democratic Rep. Jose Serrano of New York — missed the historic House votes to impeach President Donald Trump.

abstract: The president delivered his response in Michigan after he became the third U.S. president to be impeached.

abstract: The nation's top television networks had the patience to follow the House debate on impeaching President Donald Trump on Wednesday — but only to a point.

lead_paragraph: NEW YORK — The nation's top television networks had the patience to follow the House debate on impeaching President Donald Trump on Wednesday — but only to a point.
headline_main: Networks Stick With Impeachment Drama — to a Point
headline_print_headline: Networks Stick With Impeachment Drama — to a Point

abstract: The president’s favored poem, “The Snake,” isn’t about immigrants. It’s about him.
snippet: The president’s favored poem, “The Snake,” isn’t about immigrants. It’s about him.
lead_paragraph: Dating back to his days on the campaign trail, President Trump has often recited a poem called “The Snake,” as a warning about the dangers of welcoming refugees and immigrants into the country. In the Video Op-Ed above, I show how the parable is much more instructive when applied to Trump’s political rise. From his racist birther conspiracy theory to being forced to pay $2 million for using his charity for his own political gain, anyone paying close attention knew the kind of president he would be.

abstract: Tucker Carlson was grim. Sean Hannity was angry. Two networks seemed reluctant to leave their scheduled prime-time shows.
snippet: Tucker Carlson was grim. Sean Hannity was angry. Two networks seemed reluctant to leave their scheduled prime-time shows.
lead_paragraph: The impeachment debate on the floor of the House of Representatives might have been historically significant, but it took longer than expected, which meant it got in the way of two network shows that had been promoted heavily in recent weeks.
